wo\ncall 803 Iowa avenue. ti concerns undergoing heavy stresu. stones to give the giant head room\nThe name Black Friday is also ap- sitting there one evening aDout a\nvnn kkxt line. n-room cottage: cnea to eeniernDer ia. 183. wnen me \"c u\nnewlv papered; bath and gas; corner great financial crash in the stock ex- ma, ana pretty soon we neara\niicwj.' f I .I.. tna ffrir Aof in iha kit prion T tn\nJ. R. Abercromble. cnaDSe preccaing me panic oi uia r\nyear occurred.\nEighth and Iowa.\n4-21-5t\nJ other end of the house, humming a\nFOR RENT Store building, 2.\"xC0,\nbetween 4th and 5th on Kan. ave. II.\nB. Spencer. 4 23-Ct\nvmi RENT One 5 room nd one\n2-room house, 4th and 111. See J. D.\nBridges at Mayor's office, Terrell build-\nin 4 23 3t\nFOR SALE\nFOR SALE White leghorn eggs,\nWycoff strain; $1.00 for 15, or J5.00\nper IOC for incubator. Apply to O. W.\nMunford or phone 1S3. 4-Jj -il\nFOR SALE 100 feet on the corner;\nFrisco addition; 1525.? See J. P. Nail,\nPhone 149. 4-23-Ct\nFOR SALE 100 feet corner lot and\n4 room house on South Hill. Very\ncheap. See J. P. Nail, Phone 149.\n4-23-61\nLOST AND FOUND\nLOST A diamond brooch pin. Find\ner will nlease return to Morgan\nGrlbl's and receive liberal reward.\n4-23-3t\nLOST Money, time and worry. All\nof these can be saved if you trade in\nour Bargain Basement. E. E. Dugan.\nMISCELLANEOUS\nWANTED 100 head of horses to\ntur: 1.E0 Der month. See Chaa\nPearson at Thome's barber shop.\n4-1-1 mo\nWANTED To buy good second\nhand buggies. Call at the Star Wagon\nyard.\n4 24 3t\nTHE SOUTH HILL GROCERY\nMARK LANCASTER, Prep.\nEenr thiol M. clcftl tod freiL\nAnythiBfyou want ia tie poetry\nline rnu6\nIn the financial history of England\nMay 11, 1S66, is designated as Black\nFriday, as on that day began a dis\nastrous financial panic, which was\nbrought about by the failure of the\nfirm of Overend. Gurney Co., In\nLondon, who were afterward tried and\nacquitted of conspiracy to defraud.\nIn ecclesiastical history the Roman\nor Western church has frequently des\nignated Good Friday as Black Friday,\nas on that day all clerical vestments\nand altar draperies are strictly of\nblack. The term black-letter days Is\napplied to minor holidays and saints'\ndays whose names appear on calen\ndars In black letters Instead of red\nletters, as do the high days and holy\ndays. In the English calendar cer\ntain black-letter days have been re\ntained because they mark civil dates\nof Importance, such as Hilary term\nand Martinmas summer, or becauBt\nthey commemorate some public bene\nfactor.\nThe name Black Monday Is given In\nEngllbh history to Easter Monday,\nApril 14, 1360, when Edward III.\nlay with Ws host before the city of\nParis, and the weather was so stormy\nand bitter cold that many men died as\nthey eat on their horses. The term\nwas afterward extended to Include all\nEaster Mondays, and Is so used by\nShakespeare In \"The Merchant of\nVenice-' In the line \"Then It was not\nfor nothing that my nose fell a-bleed-Ing\non Blark Monday last.\" Dickens\nrefers to the schoolboy custom of re\ngarding the day for returning to\nschool after the long vacation as Black\nMonday, and an article In Household\nWords mentions \"the due observance\nof the ancient Institution of Black\nMonday,\" the eve of which was kspt\non the Saturday night, when the\nschool box was packed. In Irish his\ntory the term Black Monday was ap\nplied to the day when a number oi\nEnglish were slain In a village near\nDublin in 1209.\nAustralia has a Black Thursday In\nIts history, the uame being given la\nthe colony of Victoria to Thursdsy,\nFebruary 6. 1851, when the most tr\nrible bush fire ever known in the his\ntory of the colony raged over an lm\nmense extent of territory and the neat\nwas felt far out at sea, and birds over-\ntune; and then the first thing we knew\nwe heard the giant singing it. And\nsinging? Why, you never heard any\nthing like it; and nobody would have\nbelieved, If he hadn't beard it, that\nanybody could have such a voice.\n\"For comparison It was like the\nroar of Niagara compared to the sound\nof a little waterfall over a stone In a\nbrook. Sound? Why, I thought It\nwas going to make the walls bulge and\nblow out the windows.\nAnd it wasn't a harsh, rough voice,\nyou understand, either; It was a good,\nsmooth voice; not the most beautiful\nvoice you ever heard, but still a\nsmooth, round, deep voice of the most\namazing volume, vastly greater than\nanything you had ever dreamed of In a\nhuman voice, and it made the old\nman and me sit up in wonder.\n\"And when the giant stopped we\nfound the whole clreus was standing\naround outside the headquarters build.\nlng animal men, canvas men, drivers,\nthe whole outfit had come up to hear\nthe giant sing, and these were men,\nyou know, accustomed to strange\nthings. We had 80-odd acres In our\nreservation, but you could hear the\ngiant's voice In the furthest comer of\nIt, and I didn't know then how much\nfurther beyond; and at the first note\ntic ana singtnz we mm to give in IxVjuIj.. kj.\nthat concert ringing by the yi&at. And\nhe didn't miscalculate, fur the first\ntime the glMit sang everybody stayed\nfrom curiosity, and alter that they all\ni stayed, everywhere, because they\nwanted to.\n\"We used to stand the giant up on a\nplatform built around the ?enter pols,\nwith the band around him, where\nthere was plenty of room for him and\nwhere everybody could see him. And\nthe band would play a tune through,\nand then a flourish or two, and then\nthe giant would sing, with the band ac\ncompanying him.\n\"And he'd get the people from the\nfirst note. It was a wonder Just o see\nhim standing there, but It was a far\ngreater wonder to hear him sing. He\ndidn't make fun of it, you understand;\nhe took bis singing seriously, and so\ndid the people, for so tremendous a\nvoice had never been heard before, but\nIt was not unmusical, and altogether it\ncame pretty close to being awe-lnsplr-\nlng.\n\"You see, the giant was by far the\ngreatest man ever seen, but bis voice\nwas far greater still. Creat as he was,\nthe giant was yet a man like ourselves,\nIn human form, but his voice seemed\nsomething more than human, and It is\nan interesting fact that In all the con.\ncerts the great giant gave he was never\nonce encored. People were drawn as\nby a fascination to hear him sing, W9\nplayed to capacity from the beginning,\nthere never were before or since such\nconcerts, but there was something\nabout this colossal, stupendous, rever\nberating voice that, as I said, was\nmore than human; and while It didn't\nexactly scare 'em, any more than It\ndid those folks living out there by our\nwinter quarters, yet one song was all\nthey wanted.\n\"And it sure was wonderful. As I\nlook back at the great giant, great as\nhe actually was, he lgfims up to me\nnow greater than evertj he was a won\nder in many ways, bit I guess the\nmost wonderful thing oTTtll about him\nwas bis singing voice.\"\nLAUrAClI\nBny and 1 K, nuf.sa J S J i i\nHousehold and\nKitchen Furniture\nStoves Repaired. Telephone 411.\n406 CHICKAEHA AVR,\nDealer la\nNew and Second Hand\nGoods, Furniture\nEtc.\nv\nHtatut. Safest end Moti Comfortobl I\nCla$t Modi\nPR&SCRIBKD BY\nDR. E. CARR\nOPTICIAN\nChlckasha Ave.\n4TH YEAH IN CHICKAfeHA\n'3 CLickaaba kit,\n7-11-07:\nrno:;E 57\nW. A. HOPKINS\nhas moved to. his new\nlocation J 13 South\nPhone 79\nPhone 188\nPhone 7 IS Second Street\nRock Island Iransier\nStorage Co\nContractors and Movers of\nHetty Machinery, -Household Good,\nPianos and Safes\nLight and Heavy Transfer\na Specialty\nDADDY KLINE, Solicitor.\nL. DEl,P, Manager.\nOffice:\nKreltz Undertaking Parlot\n7-S-tf\nof It men had stopped their work and\nthen they had all come to listen.\n\"As I was saying to you, you could\nhear the giant's voice all over the res\nervation, and I didn't know how far\nbeyond; but we soon found out about\nthat. The village was only about\nthree-quarters of a mile away, and on\nstill nights and when the wind was\nright you could hear his singing then\nplainly; and It didn't exactly scars the\npeople; they all knew the giant and\nthey all liked him, but they all went\nto bed early, and that wonderful sound\ncoming to them after they had gone\nto bed did disturb 'em somewhat And\nso the old man got the giant not to\nsing after nine o'clock at night; and\nthat winter he had him practice up on\na number of songs, which of coarse\nhe was going to have the giant sing\nunder canvas la our next season on\nthe road.\n\"In those days, you know, we used\nto give a concert after the show; send\naround men before the last act selling\nk i f.ii nn the decks of coast- tickets for this concert; and tien when\niiiuic I w .1-. k.J.'l\nTik Inn caused bv Hl\n-THE-\nMisses Rouleau\nMillinery and\nDressmaking\nO. V.COr,LICiNON\nArchitect nd Structure Engine!\np..'f, Wh tms rmUlenn and eommerei!\nbuililiniri.\nmoNKllU 408 BAI.TIMOM BI.D'O\nOKLAHOMA CITY. OKI.A.\nSPR ING\nTIME\nThe time when you don't\nUow wist yea weald\nlike to eat.\nPall mi Tlinor Cash. We\nV- O\nhave in stock something that\nnjill nlease the HDDetite of the\nr\nmost fastidious\nDainty cake?, fresh troni the\noven, delicious marshmallows,\nnuts of all kind, oranges, Bana\nnas, apples and our stock of\nfresh vegetables is r-oroplete,\nnew beans, peas, new potatoes\nCall up 83 and let us tell you\nthe rest.\nTipor Gasti\nPHONE 83\n1 20 Third St.\nlng vessels.\nconflagration was exceedingly great.\nBlack Saturday was the name given\nIn Scotland to August 4, 1621, when\nthe parliament, sitting in Edinburgh,\nratified certain articles introducing\nChurch of England practices In the\nchurches of Bootland which were op\nposed to the religious convictions of\nthe Scotch Presbyterians. The violent\nthunder storm which occurred at tie\ntime, with much lightning and great\ndarkness, was held to be a manifest\ntoken of the displeasure of heaven.\nSo far as the records show, no other\nday of the week has had the adjective\nblack attached to It. Red-letter days\nare anv lucky, fortunate or auspicious\ndays, and are so called because In the\nolder liturgical works the greater holy\ndays are designated by red letters\nDickens makes one of his characters\nIn \"Bleak House\" say: \"It Is the old\ngirl's birthday, and that is the great\nest. holiday and reddest letter day In\nMr. Bapnet's calendar.\" Charles\nLamb, In his \"Oxford in the Vacation,\"\nwrites: \"The red-letter days now be\ncome, to all Intents and purposes,\ndead-letter days\nbought tickets would pass out, and\nthose that bad would stay to the coi\ncert, and sometimes half the people\nwould stay, or maybe only a quarter\nof 'em; but whatever we got that way\nwas velvet, and what the eld man was\ngoing to do was .to substitute for the\nCoffee Mousse.\nGrind one-quarter of a pound of cof\nfee, and drip enough boiling water\nthrough to make one teaspoonful of\ncoffee. Let It run through the cor\nfee slowly so as to become as strong\nas possible.\nAdd to the coffee the beaten yolks\nof two eggs and three ounces of sugar,\nput the mixture In a double boiler and\n:lr with a wooden spoon until It thick\nens. This will require about five mln.\nutes.\nAdd one tablespoonful of gelatina,\nwhich has been previously dissolved In\na wineglass of cold water. Strain the\nmixture and set aside to cool, hut not\nto harden.\nBeat one pint of whipped cream\nuntil Btlff, add the coffee to It, whip\nping until It is thick and firm.\nAs soon as thick put in a mold and\npack in ice and rock salt.\nDates as Flavoring.\nAs a change from the monotony ol\nordinary Ice creams try datcr es s\nnovel flavor and be convinced that 11\nis good. To do this you may follow\nyour customary recipe. Flavor lightly\nwith vanilla, then add two teacupfuli\nof shredded dates to each quart of the\ncream, and freeie as usual. If a pro\nnortionate quantity of dates is added\nto any ordinary cake recipe Instead of\nraisins, citron, etc., the cake will find\nfavor as a most delicate novelty.\nFigs are also an excellent substl\ntute for more ordinary flavors In Ices\nor Ice cream. They may be used In\ncakes, In pies, or in puddings, or may\nbe stewed, baked or staffed. Mixed\nwith an equal quantity of chopped nut\nmeats and made Into a blanc mange\nthat has been flavored with lemon,\nthe effect is even more appealing to\nthe sense of taste.\nC M Fechheimer\nAttorney-at-Law\nRooms 1, 2, 3, Jobnson Bcildkf\nPhone 300\nThe\nlew Early Billiard Pair\nCarries the Finest List of\nImported and Domestic Ci\ngars tn the city\n.E1REFG0T WSMSL\nAttoraeyrat-Ltw-Rear\nof Chickasaw Trust Com\npany Bank.\nTurf Exchange\nBEST PRICES\nLUMBER CO.\nBEST LUMBER\nAll Association Tracks\nNew Orleans\nOakland\nFrisco\nAnd Eastern Tracks\nRACES EVERT DAY\n66\nTurf Exchange\nBell Gr Hollotfay.44...\nProprietors of the\n.....Rock Island Sharing Parlors.....\nCompnmed Air afamffa. BUt.i In Comne\ntioB. Best shine on earth.\nThird Street, Chickasha. I. T.\nRobert J. Baze\nPHYSICIAN and SURGEON\nSpacial attention to Eye. Ear, Nose, Throat aaS\nGeneral Surgery. Office aver Brown's\n.Drug Store\nOffice Phone 624\nft evidence Phone 56\nayaVW'Wia- rr. i\n1 II I\nToo Young, Alas!\n\"Yon doubtless cursed the day you\nwere born!\" sneered the heroine, mag\nnificent In her new autumn coat, to\ngay nothing of her anger.\nThe villain winced.\n\"Believe me, no!\" he protested. \"I\nnever swore until l was eight months\nold!\"\nFor In every life, after all, there Is\na period ot Innocence, ere yet Inevlt-\nohifi dpnravitv asserts Its way. vaaB\nlnston Post. j\nThe Lucky Ones.,\n\"Don't you believe, then,\" asked the\nplain citizen, \"that 'public office la a\npublic trust'?\"\n\"Sure!\" replied the dlsgnfntled of\nflceeeker, \"It Is very like a trust\nSome fellows seem to have a regular\nmonopoly of It.\"\nForce of Habit.\n\"I wonder why Mr. Jones has such\na way of always dictating to his wife\nand why she stands It.\n\"I guess neither of them can help\nIt She used to be his typewriter.\"\